Furthermore, the effectiveness of the phosphors has been evaluated in AC applications. Security characters are printed onto cardboard substrates using a security ink containing ZAO:1Pr3+ NPs and 5 wt% CDs@ZAO:1Pr3+ NCs, applied using a brush technique. The encoded patterns are captured under daylight and UV 365 nm light conditions (
                        Fig. 12a
                        ). Compared to ZAO:1Pr3+ NPs, CDs@ZAO:1Pr3+ NCs exhibit a greater enhancement in the red colour. Therefore, we opted to utilize CDs@ZAO:1Pr3+ NCs security ink for subsequent conditions. Fig. 12b depict the anti-counterfeit labels obtained on various surfaces (paper, number plate, and magazine) using a straightforward brush mode technique. As observed in the figure, the AC pictures are barely visible under normal light but become distinctly discernible under UV 365 nm light, shows that the NCs can be directly employed as invisible security inks for AC purposes, particularly for personalized security information or passwords [93-95]. The photostability of security inks is vital for their applied scenarios. Therefore, we chose the optimized security ink to evaluate the steadiness of luminescent inks. The "puma" logo pattern is rendered on a black paper surface and observed under 365 nm UV light, as depicted in Fig. 12c. Furthermore, the AC label featuring the logo is preserved for up to 9 weeks, as shown in figure, effectively showcasing the effectiveness of the prepared security ink. As observed in the figure, the AC label exhibits minimal damage, with only a slight decrease in brightness. Moreover, the longevity of the AC images on the ceramic is examined at the temperature ranging from 50, 100, 150 and 200 °C (Fig. 12d), indicating minimal intensity loss. In contrast, the eagle pattern AC labels exhibit a consistently bright red emission under UV irradiation for up to 40 min [96-101]. The AC label shows minimal damage, with only a slight decrease in brightness (Fig. 12e). We believe that this AC method is more sophisticated and holds great promise for application in advanced AC scenarios.
